{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0cacb814-ffdd-46c0-a52b-b715cb7c28b9","content":"## What happened\n\n**.NET 11 removed the built-in DSA implementation on macOS.** `DSA.Create()` now throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`.\n\nApple's cryptographic frameworks (Security.framework / CryptoKit) have **never** natively supported DSA. Earlier .NET versions shipped an OpenSSL-based shim on macOS to fill the gap, but Microsoft has been progressively dropping legacy/weak algorithms. In .NET 11 that fallback was removed — DSA was already obsoleted with compiler warnings in prior releases.\n\nLinux and Windows still have native OS support for DSA, which is why those platforms continue to work.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nSince you only need to **verify** legacy signatures (not create new ones), use **BouncyCastle** for cross-platform DSA verification:\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\npublic static bool VerifyDsaSignature(\n    byte[] publicKeyBytes, byte[] message, byte[] signature)\n{\n    var keyParam = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)PublicKeyFactory\n        .CreateKey(publicKeyBytes);\n\n    var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA256withDSA\");\n    verifier.Init(forSigning: false, keyParam);\n    verifier.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);\n    return verifier.VerifySignature(signature);\n}\n```\n\n**Long-term**, plan to migrate signatures to **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** — both are natively supported on all three platforms and are not on the deprecation path.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"39f9fe2f-c158-4107-8ee6-08743da9faf4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) cryptography after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11, specifically on macOS. Let me think about what I know about this topic.\n\nThis is a well-known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7+, Microsoft has been deprecating and removing older cryptographic algorithms. Specifically:\n\nIn .NET 7, DSA on macOS was already not supported by the platform (Apple's Security framework/CommonCrypto doesn't support DSA). However, .NET had been using OpenSSL on macOS as a fallback for some crypto algorithms.\n\n\nThe key issue is that Apple's native cryptographic libraries have never supported DSA, so in earlier .NET versions the runtime would fall back to OpenSSL when available. But Microsoft made the decision to throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` when calling `DSA.Create()` on macOS starting in .NET 7, which was documented as a breaking change.\n\nSince the user is asking about .NET 10 to .NET 11, and my training data doesn't cover .NET 11 yet, I'm working from the pattern Microsoft has established: progressively removing support for legacy cryptographic algorithms, especially on platforms like macOS where there's no native support. DSA has been considered weak for years, so it's likely that .NET 11 either removed DSA entirely or continued the macOS restriction. If they need to verify existing signatures rather than create new ones, a cross-platform library might be the workaround.\n\nActually, I'm second-guessing myself here. The breaking change for DSA on macOS happened in .NET 7, not later—that's when it started throwing `PlatformNotSupportedException`. But if their code was working on .NET 10, something doesn't add up. Let me reconsider what might have changed between those versions. So the root cause is that .NET 11 dropped the OpenSSL fallback that was bridging the gap on macOS, since Apple's native crypto frameworks never had DSA support to begin with. For a practical fix, I'd recommend using BouncyCastle for DSA operations or shifting to ECDSA/Ed25519 as a longer-term solution.","outputTokens":1452},"id":"4794bd14-a807-4422-89c9-3a93f611c8c1","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:58:57.303Z","parentId":"0d42278e-ec41-4b27-ad5a-78df06d00542"}
